@Whoa Nellie

Woohoo! All that and another pair of (blue) Jay's.
A good omen for peaceiand frienship, y'all.

@Dan

You're right, of course. "Metaphor" is one of the most commonly misused words out there.

(Btw, in modern Greece "metaphora" means "a moving truck", or so I gathered from the word being written on all such vehicles)

@Weak

I can't imagine not wanting to set a personal best because of which puzzle it was.  I haven't set one in a long time, and I guarantee you I have no idea which puzzle it was.

Also, I have a puzzle or two that I apparently did in 0:00, because that's what the NYT website says happened. The only way I'm going to beat that is to finish it before I start it.

@Tony
I find that, two-faced solver that I am, I like my little gold stars in the present but solving in the archives frees me from the tyranny of the streak.

PS You know you can turn off the timer, tight?

@Tony

I may be wrong, but I think you can use google to look stuff up without losing the gold star. A solver can also look at the Wordplay column or even the comments without missing out on the gold star.

It's only if you use the NYT "check" or "reveal" that you end up with a blue star, right?

