{neener}

@SBK in TO

The deuce you say!

How, Torontonian muse?

@Heidi

ADZE was a gimme - "dz" is a very common letter combination in Polish, as it corresponds to one of the basic sounds of our language (for example, "dzwon" means "bell", and "dzban" means "jar"). I learned of ADZE late in life, but I was so surprised to see such Polish-like spelling in English that I instantly remembered the word.

I can only imagine the horror that the products under an American brand of tea must be... Is there anything less American than tea?

@Andrzej

Don't be dissin' Uncle Sammy, dude.

I don't want no beef with you, my Polish bro.

@Andrzej

Are you actually making an oblique reference to Sylvia Plath and her novel "The Dzwon Dzban"? 

I'm kinda kidding but that's a wild coincidence.

@ad absurdum

I'm not kidding but kinda ashamed to say I had no idea who Sylvia Plath was - I've just heard the name. I looked her up now. Sadly, "The Bell Jar" has been translated as "Szklany klosz": "[The/a] Glass Shade" (Polish does not use articles)

"Dzwon dzban" (or, more grammatically, "Dzbanny Dzwon") would have been more intriguing

@Hitch

It's not the creators, it's a decision by the NYT to make the puzzle accessible to everyone.  Unfortunately, that has the side effect of making it less enjoyable once you have a little bit of experience, so I'm not sure if that's a sustainable business mode.

It used to be assumed that when you first started solving  there would be a steep climb.  It might take several years to be able to successfully solve the end of week puzzles.  Maybe the focus on streaks and gold stars is bringing an impatience to succeed.

@Hanson

I meant sustainable over the long haul.  Long time solvers may just get bored and leave.

Will all of the new games on offer, it surprises me that they don't at least offer a set of toughened up clues.  How difficult could that be?  In some cases it would be as simple as leaving the constructor's original clue intact.

@Jeff Z

There is no reason to suspect you are not.

The problem is a Times Thursday puzzle is no longer an adequate gauge by which to judge.

@lucky13 

Here in Atlanta we have I-285, which is a ring-shaoed bypass that encirles the inner part of metro Atlanta. I think a lot of people have mistaken it for a racetrack, because they use it to recreate the "Fast and Furious" movies in real life, often using the same kinds of cars.

Seeing a Dodge Challenger moving at well over 100 mph clear your front bumper by maybe an inch is pretty memorable, and I've had that happen several times. That clue was, for me, an unfortunate "gimme."

@Bruce
Hey, Bruce, maybe you need to wear your helmet when you travel the I-285!

I'll have check out the "Fast and Furious" franchise, if I can bear it!

@Xword Junkie

Six Ks?
Does that give it a high ICK factor?

@Times Rita
I agree!  He's certainly on the national news often...  
As for the "tired fill," the long crosses are demanding, and I considered the fill  "worth it" for the sake of the trick.

@Chris
By looking across solvers. If folks who have been solving 10, 30, 50 years have noticed the puzzles suddenly getting better around 2022, the odds of them all suddenly improving around then are pretty low. 

It's not just level of difficulty, it's style of cluing. Does a clue refer to the most common answer you would associate with that clue? The next most common? The fifth most common, so that you have to think and rethink and rethink some more? I'd argue we don't get as many of that last kind now, and when we do, they are rare enough that many people complain.

@Dave Munger

Having read through the comments it seems a lot of people are confused about this puzzle.

My take is that it isn't worth the trouble to figure out exactly what is going on. I think I get it, but my feeling is, so what? My advice? Just drop it and move on. You can't win an earthquake.

